 Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Palmer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>palmer(e)</i> ‘palmer, pilgrim to the Holy Land’ (Anglo-Norman French <i>palmer</i>, Old French <i>pa(l)mer</i>, <i>paum(i)er</i>), so called from the palm branch carried by such pilgrims. The term was also used to denote an itinerant monk who traveled from shrine to shrine under a vow of poverty. This surname is also common in Ireland, where it has been recorded from the 13th century onward.","Irish: when not of English origin (see 1 above), a surname adopted for Gaelic <b>Ó Maolfhoghmhair</b> (see   Milford  ), the name of an ecclesiastical family.","Swedish (mainly <b>Palmér</b>): ornamental name formed with <i>palm</i> ‘palm tree’ + the suffix <i>-ér</i> (a derivative of Latin <i>-erius</i>) or <i>-er</i> (from German)."],"variants":[{"name":"Milford","meanings":["English (mainly Devon): habitational name from any of the many places called Milford, deriving from Old English <i>myln</i> ‘mill’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’.","Irish (Antrim and Galway): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Maolfhoghmhair</b> ‘descendant of <i>Maolgfhoghmhair</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘chief of harvest’. The Irish name was first Anglicized as <b>Mullover</b>, which was later assimilated to <i>Milford</i>. See also   Palmer  ."]},{"name":"Palmiere","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Dante, Enrico, Nicola, Salvatore, Vittorio.","Italian: from <i>palmiere</i> ‘palmer, pilgrim’. See   Palmer  ."]},{"name":"Parmer","meanings":["English: variant of   Palmer  .","Indian (northern states): variant of   Parmar  ."]},{"name":"Palmore","meanings":["Probably an altered form of English   Palmer   or an Americanized form of South German   Balmer  ."]}]},{"name":"Stephanus","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["(1997: 107;2007: 51; 2010: NA)","German and Dutch: from the Latin personal name <i>Stephanus</i>, or a Latinized (humanistic) form of its vernacular variants such as   Stephan  , a cognate of   Steven  . This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine) and in Namibia. Compare   Stevanus  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Stephan","meanings":["Variant of   Stephen  , preserving the vowels of the Greek name."]},{"name":"Stevanus","meanings":["Americanized form of German or Dutch   Stephanus  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Stephanus De Palmer was born in 1139, in Gloucestershire, England, his father, Henry De Palmer II, was 17 and his mother, Lady Ann de Walton, was 19. He married Lars Christian Norby in 1190, in Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1200, in Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 61."},"et":{"1139–1200":"1139–1200","1140–1200":"1140–1200","1155–1215":"1155–1215","1198–1260":"1198–1260","1122–1160":"1122–1160","1120–1149":"1120–1149","1190":"1190","1198":"1198","1120":"1120","1140":"1140","1260":"1260","1160":"1160","1139":"1139","1149":"1149","1215":"1215","1200":"1200","1122":"1122","1155":"1155","about 1197":"umbes 1197","Stoke, Cheshire, England":"Stoke, Cheshire, England","Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Gloustershire, England":"Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingd